e brain is embodied and embedded in affective, cultural, and historical milieus.Cappelletto considers understandings of the human brain encompassing scientific, philosophical, and visual and performance arts discourses. She examines how neuroaesthetics has constructed its field of study, exploring the ways digital renderings and scientific data have been used to produce the brain as a cultural and visual object. Tracing the intertwined histories of brain science and aesthetic theory, Embodying Art offers a strikingly original and profound philosophical account of the human brain as a living artifact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAestheticsxPhysiological aspects. 0aArtxPsychology. 0aNeurosciences and the arts. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aaffect.  aart history.  abrain imaging.  aembodiment.  aimagination.  amind-body problem.  aneuroaesthetics.  aneuroscience.  aperformance art.  aphilosophy.  apsychology.  avisual art.1 aFleck, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/capp1958640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231551526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231551526/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK